{
  "texts": [
    "Thus, y ∈ X, so Y = h(y) ∈ h[X].",
    "This shows that h[S] ∩ X ⊆ h[X].Next, we show that h satisfies:• ⊑-forth -if y ⊑ x, then h(y) ⊑ ′℘ h(x); • ⊑-back -if Y ⊑ ′℘ h(x), then ∃y: y ⊑ x and h(y) ⊑ ′℘ Y; • R-matching -∀X ∈ P ′℘: R ′℘ i (h(x)) ⊆ X iff R i (x) ⊆ h -1 [X]; • dense -∀X ∈ S ′℘ ∃x ∈ S: h(x) ⊑ ′℘ X.For ⊑-forth, if y ⊑ x, then h(y) ⊆ h(x), so h(y) ⊑ ′℘ h(x) by the definition of (AtF) ℘.For ⊑-back, suppose Y ⊑ ′℘ h(x), so Y ⊆ h(x).",
    "Since every state in (AtF) ℘ is a nonempty set of minimal points from F, there is a minimal point y ∈ Y.",
    "Then Y ⊆ h(x) implies y ⊑ x, and h(y) = {y}, so y ∈ Y implies h(y) ⊆ Y and hence h(y) ⊑ ′℘ Y.",
    "For R-matching, suppose R i (x) ̸ ⊆ h -1 [X], so x ̸ ∈ ■ i h -1 [X]."
  ]
